{"title": "Ignored Aesop", "content": "Combining Hypocritical Humor and An Aesop. The characters summarize a lesson they have learned, then immediately follow up with something that shows that they haven't learned anything after all. The characters, not quite done with reflecting on their own actions, may then proceed to further discuss what possible lessons they have learned. By the time they're finished the audience is clearly convinced that if there was ever any moral to the preceding story, it has been thoroughly and completely lost.\n\nThis is often a good way to justify Aesop Amnesia \u2014 after all, the equivalent of an Aesop-based kung-fu scene should leave everyone, including the viewer, sufficiently confused as to the purpose of the story that it's hard to hold it against the characters for failing to realize how they could apply this knowledge to other situations. This will most commonly end with characters concluding that they haven't learned anything, or they'll spend the ending of the show desperately trying to come up with an Aesop that works as a result.\n\nSee also Here We Go Again!, Spoof Aesop, Lost Aesop.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/IgnoredAesop", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/AstroBoy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Manga/Gintama", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/ShaunOfTheDead", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/HotFuzz", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheWorldsEnd", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/SimonPegg", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/FatherTed", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/WillAndGrace", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Series/TheCatherineTateShow", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Music/HidetoMatsumoto", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Music/TokyoYankees", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Music/TaijiSawada", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Theatre/DeathOfASalesman", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Theatre/SweeneyToddTheDemonBarberOfFleetStreet", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Portal2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/BobAndGeorge", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/PHD", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Webcomic/ElGoonishShive", "/pm